# START HERE — run the Agentic Loop on a blank Claude Code (2 steps)

You are about to let a **blank Claude Code (CC)** answer a research question by driving a
**Claude Science (CS)** browser tab through a research loop. You need: a blank Claude Code
open **in this folder**, and a Claude Science tab open in Chrome that the CC can control.

> ### ⚠ Before you start — do this one thing (required)
> Claude Science is a **local app**, not a website — it has no public URL and can't be bookmarked
> or searched for. The CC can only reach it if you give it the exact address:
> - **Start Claude Science** (macOS: menu-bar icon · Linux: run `claude-science`). It opens in a
>   browser tab.
> - **Copy that tab's URL** (looks like `http://localhost:8787` or `http://127.0.0.1:<number>`).
> - **Paste it into `SCIENCE_URL.txt`** in this folder (replace the `PASTE_...` line), and save.
>
> That's it. The CC then opens its **OWN new tab**, navigates straight to that URL, confirms it's
> really Claude Science, and creates its **OWN new project** there. It will **not** touch any Claude
> Science tab you already have open (that's *your* live session), and everything else in your
> account — chats, Projects, Claude Code/the assistant sessions — is strictly off-limits. If `SCIENCE_URL.txt`
> is empty it will **stop and ask you** for the URL; it will **not** go looking through your account.

Everything the CC needs is already in this folder. You only do two things.

---

## STEP 1 — start the CC (copy-paste this one line)

> **Read CLAUDE.md and bootstrap your workspace.**

That's it — this is your **only** required action until the question. The CC will, on its own:
**pre-flight its environment** (what system it's on, whether it can control Chrome, where Claude
Science is, and whether other AI models like Codex are available), create a fresh Claude Science
project (`AL-exp000-QDIS-L1` — see `project-naming-convention.md`), pre-grant the permissions
so it won't stall, upload the two PDFs from `materials/`, and then **hand you back a short "start
prompt"** and wait. If it's missing something essential (no Chrome control, can't find CS) it will
write `NEEDS_HUMAN.md` telling you exactly what to fix.

*(No special launcher needed. If your CC didn't auto-read CLAUDE.md, the line above tells it to.
The only clicks you may need: approving a permission card if one pops up.)*

---

## STEP 2 — give it the question

When the CC says it's ready, it will show you a **start prompt** to paste into it. That start
prompt contains a blank you fill with the research question — **paste the question exactly as a
curious scientist would type it**, no editing. For this pilot the question is:

> **Which disease is the best target for treating it with ergothioneine?**

Paste that, send it, and the CC runs the loop on its own. It checks the CS tab every ~10 minutes
(that's normal — not stuck). **When a permission card pops up in the CS tab, click approve.**

---

## What you get at the end
A folder `OUTPUT/QDIS_arm_L_run1/` containing the final answer (`answer.md`), any figures, and the
full step-by-step of what happened (`process_trace.json`). Plus `run_log.md` and `RUN_REPORT.md` at
the top of this folder.

**This is a first try — we just want to see how far one blank CC gets.** No baseline, no scoring
yet. If the CC gets stuck it will write `NEEDS_HUMAN.md` telling you exactly what to do.

## If something goes wrong
Give the whole folder (whatever it managed to produce) back to us, or ask your helper (the assistant) to
write a short **blackbox report** — what happened, where it stalled, what CS produced — and hand
that back. A partial result is useful; that's the point of a pilot.
